								<a name="content"></a><p class="lead"><strong>The word "email" is short for electronic mail. It is very common way to send messages, documents and other data from one computer user to another, typically through the Internet. </strong></p class="lead">
 <hr>

<h4>Email Account</h4>


<p>An email account and address are unique to the individual user.</p>								<p>Many people have an email account where they work or go to school. Many people also have a personal email account that is separate from a work or school email.</p>
								<p>Regardless of the kind of email account, all email addresses, like Web addresses, are made up of common components or parts.</p>
								<p>All email addresses have three main parts:</p>
								<p><strong>username@domainname.suffix</strong></p>
								<ol>
									<li><strong>user name</strong></li>
									<li><strong>the symbol "@"</strong></li>
									<li><strong>domain name and suffix</strong></li>
								</ol>
								<p>The <strong>user name</strong> for your email account may be one you choose, especially if it is a personal email. It is very common for people to have personal email addresses through Google, Yahoo!, Hotmail and other companies like that.</p>
								<p>For personal email accounts, people can choose anything they want for a user name, as long as it is still available. People can have a user name that has letters and numbers in it and often use their name, a nickname, or some other word, phrase or combination to create a unique user name.</p>
								<p>If you have email at work or school, user names often have particular formats or rules and your user name may be given or assigned to you.</p>
								<p>After the user name, you will see a symbol, <strong>@</strong>. This symbol separates the user name from the domain name.</p>
								<p>The <strong>domain name</strong> may be long or short and may have more than one part. It will end with a domain suffix such as .com or .org or .edu or some other suffix.</p>
								<p>Many email addresses are very specific and case sensitive. This means, if an email address has capital letters in it, it is best to make sure you use them and make sure to include and symbols you see as well.</p>
